commits.message:
Print regions in `type_name`.

Currently they are skipped, which is a bit weird, and it sometimes
causes malformed output like `Foo<>` and `dyn Bar<, A = u32>`.

Most regions are erased by the time `type_name` does its work. So all
regions are now printed as `'_` in non-optional places. Not perfect, but
better than the status quo.

`c_name` is updated to trim lifetimes from MIR pass names, so that the
`PASS_NAMES` sanity check still works. It is also renamed as
`simplify_pass_type_name` and made non-const, because it doesn't need
to be const and the non-const implementation is much shorter.

The commit also renames `should_print_region` as
`should_print_optional_region`, which makes it clearer that it only
applies to some regions.

Fixes #145168.

Auto merge of #145284 - nnethercote:type_name-print-regions, r=lcnr

Print regions in `type_name`.

Currently they are skipped, which is a bit weird, and it sometimes causes malformed output like `Foo<>` and `dyn Bar<, A = u32>`.

Most regions are erased by the time `type_name` does its work. So all regions are now printed as `'_` in non-optional places. Not perfect, but better than the status quo.

`c_name` is updated to trim lifetimes from MIR pass names, so that the `PASS_NAMES` sanity check still works. It is also renamed as `simplify_pass_type_name` and made non-const, because it doesn't need to be const and the non-const implementation is much shorter.

The commit also renames `should_print_region` as `should_print_optional_region`, which makes it clearer that it only applies to some regions.

Fixes rust-lang/rust#145168.

issue.title: Supporting multiprocessing models other than fork(2)
issue.body:
Greetings everyone,

As seen with #250 , anything Python changes might render "legacy" getmail unsupported. The changes from Python 2 to 3 made it obvious, but so are changes made within Python 3 (especially the change from `fork` to `spawn`,  unforeseen to me on MacOS with Python 3.8, and more recently on 3.14).

In the current state, getmail will have trouble with spawn, which is a shared concern between various actors. For Python multiprocessing (using `spawn`), pickle will be used for ser/des when spawning subprocesses, and pickle is limited in the type of objects it can handle (as seen in #250 ). Supporting this requires an extensive cleanup of `logging`, `tempfile` usage and `SSLContext` in getmail, as these objects are not pickable. One would even argue about serializing sensitive objects like SSLContext, but in the current use case the impact negligible.

After looking at it yesterday, I see different paths forward, but each have their tradeoffs @rpuntaie :
- use force fork method, as [suggested in Python docs](https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.html#contexts-and-start-methods). The tradeoff is that if getmail ends up multithreading "unknowingly" [like it might happen on MacOS with higher level libs](https://github.com/python/cpython/issues/77906), getmail will crash. (Note: the issue would be the exact same with the legacy method of os.fork(2) of getmail5);
- patch getmail classes to support spawn. From my short testing, it involves dropping the custom-made logging class and use Python logging module instead (which seems to be onpar feature-wise, [original comment](https://github.com/getmail6/getmail6/blob/83ca7adfaaef9482a887be5126d18f2c6feeb74e/getmailcore/logging.py#L7) does not seem to apply any more), redesign the temporary files communication between parent <> child, and prevent [SSLContext sharing between processes](https://github.com/getmail6/getmail6/blob/83ca7adfaaef9482a887be5126d18f2c6feeb74e/getmailcore/_retrieverbases.py#L126). Tradeoff: significant departure from legacy, and extensive testing ahead.

comment.body:
Forgot to drop my humble opinionated view (:

I would leave the current fork method and revisit in case someone reports crashes in the future. getmail is a generous wrapper around imaplib. If it crashes because someone forgets to adequately handle fork in its MT lib, more critical Python projects will be bit by it before getmail ends up being affected. IMHO the investment is not worth at this stage, but again that is a personal opinion

I suggest we add a reference to the current issue in the comment next to the Process, so as in the future, if it happens, someone would not bang head to much to figure out what exactly happens, and what needs to be done

commits.message: added showBuf function and using tabs for terminal
changed netrw vsplit to Buffer, installed vimwiki and commentary
Remove `verify_inside_clippy_dir` since we always set the current directory.
Make `dev serve` actually detect all updates
Add helper function for creating cargo commands.
Use `track_caller` more for better error spans in `clippy_dev`
Inline `cargo_clippy_path` and add a note about removing it when possible

`similar_names` stop linting for 3-char names (#15100)

fixes rust-lang/rust-clippy#14869

Added a simple check if both chars are of length 3
If they are, we skip the check for that pair.

This won't handle the 4 v 3 case.
Not sure if this was the intent of the issue.

Also saw we have some hardcoded exemptions for `set, get` and `lhs, rhs`
Tried removing them thinking they would be handled by the new condition.
But we have to keep because they allow for `bla_lhs` v `bla_rhs` to be
skipped

issue.title: Debug: uv sync fail for pyproject.toml
issue.body:
Due to version problem when handling with uv sync one will get 
```
 Ã— No solution found when resolving dependencies for split (python_full_version >= '3.9' and python_full_version < '3.11'):
  â•°â”€â–¶ Because the requested Python version (>=3.8) does not satisfy Python>=3.11 and numpy==2.3.1 depends on Python>=3.11, we can conclude that
      numpy==2.3.1 cannot be used.
      And because your project depends on numpy==2.3.1 and your project requires traceroot-framework[all], we can conclude that your project's
      requirements are unsatisfiable.
```
This could be easily solved by chaining the toml file to >=3.11
#54
